Moustier-Ventadour, Corrèze, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France","Moustier-Ventadour, Corrèze, Limousin, France":"Moustier-Ventadour, Corrèze, Limousin, France","Montpellier,34172,Hérault,Occitanie,FRANCE,":"Montpellier, Hérault, Occitanie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Adélaïde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic origin (via French  <b>Adélaïde</b> ), from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>heid</i> ‘kind, sort’. It was borne in the 10th century by the wife of the Holy Roman Emperor Otto the Great. She became regent after his death and was revered as a saint. The given name increased in popularity in England during the 19th century, when it was borne by the wife of King William IV; she was the daughter of the ruler of the German duchy of Saxe-Meiningen. The Australian city of Adelaide was named in her honour."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Adélaïde de MONTPELLIER was born about 1132, in Montpellier, Hérault, Occitanie, France as the daughter of Guillaume de Montpellier IV  Seigneur d'Aumelas, de Montarnaud, de Popian and de Saint-Pons. She had at least 5 sons with Ebles III de VENTADOUR."},"et":{"ABT 1132–":"umbes 1132–Surnud","1129–1172":"1129–1172","1132–Female":"1132–Surnud","1140–Male":"1140–Surnu